    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Ok, so I'm putting myself into the shoes of a user who wants to run an ethereum node and ended up using `trinity`. The user may not know (and care) how `trinity` is layered what different technologies it uses underneath to accomplish what it does.\r\n\r\nLet's consider the user is having trouble to connect to the network. Running `trinity` with `-l debug` I think it would be beneficial to see messages such as the following even though they are technically coming from the `p2p` layer which may be an independent project.\r\n\r\n```\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Sending msg with cmd_id: 0\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Waiting for 32 bytes from <Node(0x7a34@35.227.38.243)>\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Waiting for 32 bytes from <Node(0x7a34@35.227.38.243)>\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Got msg with cmd_id: 1\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Successfully decoded Disconnect (cmd_id=1) msg: {'reason': 4, 'reason_name': 'too_many_peers'}\r\n09:42:56 DEBUG: Could not complete handshake with <Node(0x7a34@35.227.38.243)>: HandshakeFailure('ETHPeer <Node(0x7a34@35.227.38.243)> disconnected before completing handshake: too_many_peers',)\r\n```",
